      "a": "The Fugitive Slave Act of 1850, included as part of the Compromise, actually intensified Northern opposition to slavery rather than resolving sectional tensions, because it required Northern citizens and officials to actively participate in the capture and return of freedom-seeking people. Many Northerners who had been willing to tolerate slavery as a distant Southern institution found themselves morally implicated by a law that made them complicit in returning people to bondage on Northern streets. The Act energized the antislavery movement, drove thousands of Black Americans to flee to Canada, and produced dramatic rescue attempts in cities like Boston and Syracuse that became celebrated acts of resistance, undermining the compromise's goal of sectional peace.",
