      "a": "The Supreme Court's interpretation of the Fourteenth Amendment in the Slaughterhouse Cases (1873) and United States v. Cruikshank (1876) severely limited the amendment's protective scope before it could be effectively applied. In Cruikshank, the Court ruled that the federal government could only protect citizens from state violations of their rights, not from private violence — meaning that white supremacist organizations like the Ku Klux Klan could terrorize Black Southerners without triggering federal intervention. This judicial construction essentially gutted the enforcement provisions of the Reconstruction amendments by removing federal jurisdiction over the widespread private violence that was the primary mechanism of Black disenfranchisement and oppression in the South.",
