    "sampleSolution": {
      "thesis": "The escalating sectional crisis between 1845 and 1860 did represent a fundamental breakdown of the political system, but this breakdown was caused not simply by disagreement over slavery's expansion but by the inability of existing political institutions — the two-party system, the Senate's balance of power, and the Supreme Court's authority — to contain a conflict in which the two sections held irreconcilable positions on the nature of property, labor, and constitutional rights.",
      "contextualization": "The Missouri Compromise of 1820 had established a framework for managing sectional conflict over slavery by maintaining a geographic boundary and a Senate balance between slave and free states. The Mexican War and its territorial acquisitions reopened the question of slavery's expansion in a context where the old compromises no longer held, and the political parties that had previously transcended sectional divisions — the Whigs and Democrats — collapsed under the pressure of an issue that could not be neutralized through logrolling and coalition building.",
      "evidence_point1": "The institutional breakdown accelerated through a series of escalating crises: the Compromise of 1850 required Daniel Webster to sacrifice his political career and still produced Northern fury over the Fugitive Slave Act; the Kansas-Nebraska Act destroyed the Missouri Compromise and produced \"Bleeding Kansas,\" a small civil war that presaged the larger one; and the Dred Scott decision destroyed the possibility of a congressional settlement by declaring that Congress had no authority to restrict slavery anywhere in the territories.",
      "evidence_point2": "The collapse of the Whig Party and the emergence of the explicitly sectional Republican Party demonstrated that the political system could no longer contain the slavery issue within a framework of national parties. When Lincoln won the presidency in 1860 without a single Southern electoral vote, Southern leaders concluded that their minority position within the constitutional system was permanent — the population growth of the free states meant they would never again control the presidency through the existing political process.",
      "analysis": "The crisis was a genuine breakdown rather than simply a failure of political will because the underlying conflict was not susceptible to political compromise: Southern slaveholders required not merely the toleration but the legal protection and potential expansion of slavery, while the free-labor ideology of the Republican Party held that slavery was a moral wrong that must be placed on a path to extinction. These positions could not be permanently split the difference through legislation, which is why each successive compromise simply generated a new and more explosive crisis rather than resolving the underlying conflict."
    },
