      "a": "The American Federation of Labor complicated the goal of broad worker solidarity by organizing exclusively along craft lines and explicitly excluding unskilled workers, recent immigrants from Southern and Eastern Europe, women, and most Black workers from membership. Samuel Gompers justified this exclusionary strategy as pragmatic — skilled craftsmen had the greatest bargaining leverage and could win concrete gains — but it left the vast majority of industrial workers unorganized and created deep divisions between the AFL's relatively privileged craft workers and the poorly paid laborers of mass production industries. The AFL's willingness to accept racial exclusion in affiliated unions in exchange for organizational stability revealed that the labor movement's vision of solidarity was limited by the racial and ethnic hierarchies of Gilded Age America.",
