    "sampleSolution": {
      "a": "Clinton's signing of the Personal Responsibility and Work Opportunity Reconciliation Act of 1996, which effectively ended the federal welfare entitlement established by the New Deal, alienated the liberal wing of the Democratic Party that had long defended the social safety net as a core party commitment. Similarly, Clinton's support for NAFTA over the strong opposition of labor unions — one of the party's core constituencies — deepened the sense among working-class Democrats that their interests were being sacrificed for the preferences of corporate donors and free-trade economists. These centrist policy choices demonstrated that triangulation could win electoral victories while fracturing the Democratic coalition, generating the progressive disillusionment that would fuel primary challenges and third-party votes for years afterward.",
      "b": "Newt Gingrich's Contract with America nationalized the 1994 midterms by framing them as a referendum on Clinton's first term and presenting a unified conservative legislative agenda that gave Republican candidates a coherent message in every district. After winning the House majority, Gingrich used procedural tactics — limiting committee deliberation, centralizing power in the Speaker's office, and pursuing aggressive oversight investigations of the Clinton administration — to maximize partisan conflict rather than seek bipartisan compromise. The two government shutdowns of 1995-96 demonstrated that Republicans were willing to paralyze the federal government to force spending cuts, establishing a new template for using budget confrontations as political weapons that would define congressional polarization for the following three decades.",
      "c": "Clinton-era polarization was driven significantly by cultural and personal animosity — the politics of the culture wars over abortion, gay rights, and gun control, combined with the personal attacks and ultimately the impeachment proceedings surrounding Clinton's private conduct. Obama-era polarization was driven more by structural and ideological forces: the rise of the Tea Party in 2009-2010 reflected a grassroots conservative mobilization against government spending and the Affordable Care Act that was reinforced by partisan media ecosystems, gerrymandered districts, and the self-sorting of Americans into politically homogeneous communities. While Clinton faced intense partisan opposition, the institutional norms of bipartisan governance still held in many areas; by the Obama era, those norms had significantly eroded, making routine legislative functions like confirming executive appointments and passing budgets sites of unprecedented partisan conflict."
    },
